AB  - Research on family businesses' risk-taking behavior generally assumes that family businesses are risk averters. However, most of these studies have focused on one single decision, ignoring the fact that family businesses need to make multiple risk decisions in certain cases. Based on the perspectives of narrow-framing and broad-framing in prospect theory, this paper examines the risk appetite of family enterprises in corporate venture capital investments. We focus on two key risky decisions in corporate venture capital activities - the number of investments and venture relatedness and propose that family businesses tend to adopt risk-diversification strategies to control the overall risk. Therefore, there will be positive relationships between the number of investments and venture relatedness. Moreover, such relationships will be moderated by the type of family firm. Analysis of 180 largest Chinese manufacturing listed family companies supports our hypotheses, confirming a need to take the heterogeneity of family firms fully into account. © (2023) by Aussino Academic Publishing House All rights reserved.
