AB  - Rare disasters have had a significant impact on China′s economic development, particularly affecting the survival and growth of small and microenterprises. Compared with large and medium-sized enterprises, small and microenterprises face a more serious problem of difficult and expensive financing. This paper studies the decline in residents′ willingness to resume work and the risk of business shutdown caused by rare disaster impacts on economic development, as well as the heterogeneity between small and medium-sized enterprises and large and medium-sized enterprises. In the first part, we present three key facts about the risks of rare disasters and their impact on small and micro-enterprises, based on a literature review and summary. First, the impact of rare disaster risks on economic development lasts for a long time and affects a wide range of factors. It is necessary for the government to intervene with appropriate fiscal and monetary policies. Second, China′s small and microenterprises receive less credit support from the financial system, and the phenomenon of financing constraints is very serious. Third, Rare disasters, especially pandemics, have a significant negative impact on capital utilization rates and employees′ willingness to return to work. In the second part, we construct a DSGE model including large and medium enterprises and small and microenterprises. The basic structure of the model includes the following: households obtain income through wages, interest in deposits and transfer payments to purchase retail goods; labor unions are responsible for packaging and providing wage-sticky labor provided by families to production enterprises; large and medium-sized enterprises and small and microenterprises utilize capital and labor to produce two types of intermediate goods; small and microenterprises face Kiyotaki and Moore type financing constraints; monopolistic competitive retailers package intermediate goods produced by large and medium enterprises and small and microenterprises to generate retail goods; and the central bank implements monetary policy through the extended Taylor rule. Assuming that the probability of disasters has a certain continuity, the impact on the operating rate of enterprises and the willingness to supply labor of residents occurs simultaneously with the onset of the disaster, and the impact of disaster follows a logarithmic first-order autoregressive process. In the third part, the parameters of the model are calibrated and Bayesian estimated. The fixed parameters in the model are mainly obtained by referring to the research results in the literature and combined with the actual situation of China. The dynamic parameters in the model are obtained by Bayesian estimation based on the quarterly data of China′s economy from the second quarter of 2004 to the fourth quarter of 2018. The estimated value, significance interval, acceptance rate, MCMC convergence diagnostics and prior and posterior distributions of Bayesian estimation all show that the estimated parameter values are robust. In the fourth part, we simulate and analyze the effect of the impact of rare disasters on the real economy and compare the heterogenous behaviors of small and microenterprises and large and medium-sized enterprises under different financing constraints and degrees of impact of the pandemic. The simulation analysis results show that in the absence of policy intervention, rare disasters lead to a decrease in total investment, an increase in unemployment, and an increase in inflation, which places greater downward pressure on the economy. Compared with large and medium-sized enterprises, small and microenterprises with financing constraints are more negatively affected by the impact of the pandemic. Starting from alleviating the financing constraints of small and microenterprises and implementing loose monetary policy, this paper discusses the effect of rescue measures with different intensities on promoting economic recovery. The weakening of the financing constraints of small and microenterprises can increase the total social investment and employment. Loose monetary policy helps hedge against the negative effects of rare disasters in the short term but does not have a long-term growth effect. In summary, the long-standing financing constraints of small and microenterprises make such enterprises face greater risk after the rare disaster shock. After the shock, without government intervention and support policies, more employment and credit resources flow to large and medium-sized enterprises. This further squeezes the development space of small and microenterprises and has a more adverse impact on economic recovery and long-term development. Therefore, it is necessary and urgent for state and local governments to increase support for small and microenterprises. © (2023), (Zhejiang University). All Rights Reserved.
