AB  - The unprecedented COVID-19 pandemic and its resulting business closures have generated enormous losses to the world economy. One of the major victims of the COVID-19 outbreak are micro, small, and medium-sized enterprises (MSMEs). Due to the pandemic and induced lockdowns, this sector reported a sudden fall in demand and sales, unavailability of raw materials due to supply chain disruptions, transportation problems and finally business closures for many units throughout the country. The impacts of any crisis are never gender-neutral and as such it has affected everyone in some way or the other. While each individual faced unprecedented challenges, the women entrepreneurs also had to bear the brunt of the economic and social fallout from the COVID pandemic. Further, the strong negative repercussions of demanding household responsibilities, childcare, care of sick family members and all usual home chores amplified due to lockdown, affected the women, particularly in businesses everywhere. Thus, this paper aims to study the impacts of the COVID-19 pandemic on women micro businesses in the Cuttack city of Odisha. The objective of the study is to assess the impact of the COVID- 19 pandemic on the socio-economic status of women entrepreneurs. The related hypothesis, which the study would attempt to test is that there is no impact of COVID 19 pandemic on the socio-economic conditions of the women entrepreneurs. The study is based on primary data from 40 samples collected through a semi-structured questionnaire. The study adopts a qualitative research design which is the thematic analysis, to highlight the impacts of the COVID-19 on their economic and social life. It has used descriptive statistics for the data analysis. The study reveals that the majority of respondents (women entrepreneurs) were severely affected by the pandemic and they faced several challenges related to financial and mental crises, increased household responsibilities, decrease in sales and demand, business closures, mobility problems etc. They also mentioned no significant Government support and only a few were able to adopt online businesses during the crisis. The study has a positive implication for the policymakers to take into consideration the needs and necessities of such women micro-entrepreneurs to support and empower them in their endeavour, as empowering a woman of a household, is like empowering the entire household for generations to come. © 2024 Nova Science Publishers, Inc. All rights reserved.
